'''''Loco''''' is a video game developed by [[Antony Crowther]] and released by [[Alligata]] for the [[Commodore 64]] in 1984.<ref name="giantlist"/>  ''Loco'' is a clone of the 1982 Sega arcade game ''[[Super Locomotive]]''. Ports for the [[ZX Spectrum]] and [[Atari 8-bit computers]] were released in 1986. The ZX Spectrum port was developed by Richard Stevenson, David Wright and Nigel Speight.{{cn|date=July 2017}}. The music for the game is a C64 remake of [[Jean-Michel Jarre]]'s [[Equinoxe|Equinoxe 5 and 6]] by [[Ben Daglish]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Loco|magazine=[[Retro Gamer]]|publisher=Imagine Publishing|issue=70|pages=84â€“89}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Making Of: Loco|magazine=[[Retro Gamer]]|publisher=Imagine Publishing|issue=196|page=44}}</ref>

Crowther's subsequent ''Suicide Express'' is related to ''Loco'', though not an official sequel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Suicide Express|url=http://www.personalcomputernews.co.uk/pcnb/html/080/personal_computer_news_080_gameplay_suicide_express.html|last1=Skinner|first1=Bryan|website=[[Personal Computer News]]|access-date=February 18, 2021}}</ref>

==Reception==
In July 1984 ''Loco'' was awarded game of the month by ''[[Personal Computer Games]]'' magazine. {{cn|date=July 2017}}

